Assignment Guidelines
How to Achieve Maximum Marks in the Final Group Project
This guide explains what strong projects look like and how to perform at an Excellent level.
1. Start with a Strong Problem
High-mark projects:
• Choose a real, relevant media problem
• Clearly define the target audience
• Explain why the problem matters
• Clearly justify why computing and AI are needed
Avoid:
• Vague problems like “improve social media”
• Generic AI ideas with no clear purpose
• Solutions that do not require data
Tip:
If you remove the data and AI and the idea still works, your problem is too weak.
2. Design the System Before Building Anything
High-mark projects:
• Draw a clear system architecture diagram
• Show inputs, processing, outputs
• Explain algorithm logic step by step
• Explain how users interact with the system
Strong groups clearly explain:
• What data enters the system
• What happens to the data
• What the AI does with it
• What the final output looks like
Tip:
Think like an engineer, not just a designer.
3. Take Data Seriously
To score highly in the Data criterion:
• Use a structured dataset with at least 100 records
• Clearly describe where the data came from
• Clean and preprocess the data
• Explain what you removed, changed, or transformed
High-mark groups:
• Show screenshots or code snippets of cleaning steps
• Explain why preprocessing is necessary
• Connect analysis results to system design
Avoid:
• Using raw data without explanation
• Including charts with no interpretation
4. Produce Meaningful Analysis
Minimum requirements:
• At least 3 visualisations
• At least 2 data-driven insights
To get maximum marks:
• Ensure visualisations are clearly labelled
• Explain what each graph shows• Extract insights that influence your AI system
Example of strong insight:
“Data shows that posts containing emotional keywords receive 40 percent higher engagement.
Therefore, our AI content generator prioritises emotionally expressive language.”
Avoid:
• Describing the graph instead of analysing it
• Presenting obvious or superficial insights
5. Integrate AI Properly
High-mark AI integration:
• Is central to the solution
• Uses analysed data
• Produces meaningful output
• Is clearly explained conceptually
Students must explain:
• What type of AI is used
• What inputs it takes
• What outputs it produces
• Its limitations
• Potential bias or risks
Avoid:
• Just embedding ChatGPT in a mockup
• Saying “we used AI” without explanation
• Not understanding how the AI works
If you cannot explain your AI clearly during Q and A, marks will drop.
6. Build a Prototype That Demonstrates Logic
High-mark prototypes:
• Actually demonstrate system logic
• Show data flowing through the system
• Show AI output
• Show user interaction
The prototype does not need to be advanced, but it must:
• Work logically
• Reflect your system design
Avoid:
• Static slides pretending to be an app
• Screenshots without functionality
• No live demonstration
7. Write Like a UCA Student
Your report should:
• Be structured clearly
• Explain technical ideas logically
• Connect directly to COMP1073 concepts
• Include diagrams
• Include data analysis clearly
Strong reports:
• Explain algorithms in simple structured language
• Explain AI conceptually
• Discuss ethical risks like bias and privacy
• Reflect critically on limitations
Avoid:
• Overly descriptive writing with no technical explanation
• Copying definitions from the internet
• Ignoring ethical implications
8. Prepare for Q and A
To secure high marks:
• Every member must understand the project
• Be ready to explain data cleaning
• Be ready to explain AI logic
• Be ready to justify design decisions
If one member cannot explain core components, marks may be affected.
Final Advice for Maximum Marks
To score in the Excellent range:
• Choose a meaningful problem
• Design before building
• Analyse data deeply
• Integrate AI properly
• Demonstrate understanding
• Reflect critically
The strongest projects are those that show both conceptual understanding and technical application.
